{
  "answer": "**In Allama Iqbal's *Shikwa* (Bang-E-Dara Part 3, chapter 20), the speaker recalls the Muslim conquests and presence in Spain—part of Europe under Muslim rule for centuries—as one of the great historical achievements of the Muslim ummah.**[^1]\n\nThis reference occurs amid a litany of Muslim military and spiritual triumphs, where the speaker boasts to God of having spread Islam across continents: \"We called the prayer in Europe’s churches, burning with Your light.\" This alludes to the Umayyad conquest of Visigothic Spain in 711 CE under Tariq ibn Ziyad, after which Muslims (calling the *adhan*, or Islamic call to prayer) converted churches like the Cathedral of Córdoba into mosques, ruling Al-Andalus until 1492.[^1]\n\n**No more explicit mentions of \"Spain,\" \"Andalusia,\" or \"Córdoba\" appear in *Shikwa* itself.** (Iqbal references Córdoba separately in chapter 2, *Bilad-e-Islamiya*, and Andalusia in chapter 23, *Tarana-e-Milli*, but those are distinct poems.) The corpus has no other Iqbal works matching \"Shikwa.\"\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch.20 *Shikwa* [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/20-shikwa/translation/#p-e1af7a).",
